{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504353"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:14:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:14:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2325"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2325"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.6,0.03,0.05,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111924"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2325"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93988"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1286"},{"type":"tags","id":"1537"},{"type":"tags","id":"2143"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1551"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111924"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old carpenter falls and injures his right hand. He complains of severe pain in the wrist and cannot flex or extend the joint. There is considerable bruising and tenderness around the joint. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plaster backslab","Open reduction and fixation with compression screw","Radial styloidectomy","Wrist strapping with tape","Cylinder splint"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s fall has caused a scaphoid fracture that is shown to be displaced on the X-ray. This requires surgical intervention. \u003Cstrong\u003EOpen reduction and fixation with compression screw\u003C/strong\u003E prevents scaphoid non-union, and allows earlier mobilisation and faster return to prior function (Image). The screw can be inserted percutaneously (minimally invasive) or via open surgery, depending on severity of displacement and surgeon preference.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlaster immobilisation is suited for non-displaced scaphoid fractures. Radial styloidectomy is used to treat symptomatic arthritis of the wrist. Wrist strapping would not sufficiently immobilise the joint for the fracture to heal properly.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Internal fixation is the preferred option for displaced scaphoid fractures."],"references":["Arsalan-Werner A, Sauerbier M, Mehling IM. Current concepts for the treatment of acute scaphoid fractures. Eur J Trauma Emerg Surg. 2016 Feb;42(1):3-10. doi: 10.1007/s00068-015-0587-8.","Phillips TG, Reibach AM, Slomiany WP. Diagnosis and management of scaphoid fractures. Am Fam Physician. 2004 Sep 1;70(5):879-84. PMID: 15368727.","Grewal R. Surgery versus cast immobilisation for acute scaphoid fractures. Lancet 2020; 396:362-63."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93988"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2325"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17539"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22056"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17539"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"im